n(self.tree) // 4 - 1, index, new_haiku) # Example usage haikus = [ \\"Does lazy eye missnChances lost like morning dewnGolden sunrise fades\\", \\"Does thoughtless soul ignorenVoices whispering wisdomnMoonlight's silent shore\\" ] segment_tree = SegmentTree(haikus) print(segment_tree.range_query(0, 1)) # Output: ['Does lazy eye missnChances lost like morning dewnGolden sunrise fades', 'Does thoughtless soul ignorenVoices whispering wisdomnMoonlight's silent shore'] segment_tree.update_haiku(0, \\"Does lazy eye sleepnChances lost like morning dewnGolden sunrise dreams\\") print(segment_tree.range_query(0, 1)) # Output: ['Does lazy eye sleepnChances lost like morning dewnGolden sunrise dreams', 'Does thoughtless soul ignorenVoices whispering wisdomnMoonlight's silent shore'] \`\`\` Now, I have implemented both the recursive and iterative segment trees. I can see that the recursive implementation uses a recursive function to build the tree, while the iterative implementation uses a loop to build the tree level by level. Both implementations support the 'range_query' and 'update' operations, and can be used to store and manage a collection of haikus about foolish behavior. Let me think about the time and space complexity of the two implementations. The recursive implementation has a time complexity of O(n log n) and a space complexity of O(n), where n is the number of haikus. The iterative implementation also has a time complexity of O(n log n) and a space complexity of O(n). In conclusion, both the recursive and iterative segment trees can be used to store and manage a collection of haikus about foolish behavior, and support the 'range_query' and 'update' operations. The choice of implementation depends on the specific requirements of the problem and the personal preference of the programmer. To summarize, I have implemented a segment tree data structure to store and manage a collection of haikus about foolish behavior, using both recursive and iterative approaches. T